# Build output: store verbatim, no line-ending normalization, treat as binary.
# Keeps prebuilt .next identical across local (Windows) and EC2 (Linux).
#
# `-merge` matters as much as the other two. These files are regenerated whole
# on every `next build`, so when two people both build, git was attempting a
# line-by-line three-way merge on hundreds of generated/binary files and
# producing pages of conflicts (and, for binaries, meaningless output). With
# -merge git makes no attempt: a clash is a plain pick-one-side, resolved with
#
#     git checkout --ours .next   # or --theirs
#     git add .next
#
# and then a fresh `npm run build`, since whichever side you keep is stale the
# moment the sources differ. NOTE: .next is committed deliberately — the EC2 box
# runs `next start` without building (see .gitignore) — so it must stay tracked.
.next/** -text -diff -merge
